<ArticleLayout
  title="Bathroom Vanity Storage: What to Sort Before Buying Organisers"
  description="Before buying bathroom vanity organisers, sort daily items, cosmetics, razors, medicines, hair tools, spare supplies and cleaning products, then measure drawers, shelves, pipes and access."
  category="Bathroom"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  readingTime="9 minute read"
  showAffiliateDisclosure={false}
  image="/images/bathroom.webp"
  imageAlt="A bathroom vanity with warm finishes, practical drawer storage and soft natural light"
>
  <p>
    Bathroom vanity storage can become messy even in a well-kept bathroom. Daily products sit
    on the bench, spare tubes fall to the back of drawers, razors mix with cosmetics, and
    under-sink shelves become a collection point for half-used bottles and cleaning products.
  </p>
  <p>
    It is tempting to fix the problem by buying drawer dividers, trays, baskets or under-sink
    organisers. But vanity storage works better when the items are sorted first.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying organisers, check what actually needs to stay in the vanity, what should be
    removed, what needs controlled access, and what dimensions you are working with.
  </p>
  <p>
    This guide explains what to sort before buying bathroom vanity organisers.
  </p>

  <h2>Start by emptying one section at a time</h2>
  <p>
    You do not need to empty the whole bathroom at once.
  </p>
  <p>Start with one vanity zone:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>benchtop</li>
    <li>top drawer</li>
    <li>lower drawer</li>
    <li>under-sink cabinet</li>
    <li>side cabinet</li>
    <li>medicine or first-aid area</li>
    <li>makeup area</li>
    <li>hair care area</li>
    <li>cleaning product area</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Sorting one section at a time makes it easier to see what the vanity is actually holding.
    It also prevents the common problem where items are moved from one messy area into
    another messy area.
  </p>
  <p>
    As you sort, group items by use rather than by where they currently sit.
  </p>

  <h2>Separate daily items from spare items</h2>
  <p>
    Vanity storage should make daily routines easier.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying organisers, separate daily-use items from backup supplies.
  </p>
  <p>Daily items may include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>toothbrushes</li>
    <li>toothpaste</li>
    <li>cleanser</li>
    <li>moisturiser</li>
    <li>deodorant</li>
    <li>sunscreen</li>
    <li>hair brush</li>
    <li>comb</li>
    <li>shaving items</li>
    <li>contact lens supplies</li>
    <li>daily makeup</li>
    <li>daily skincare</li>
    <li>current hair products</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Spare items may include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>extra toothpaste</li>
    <li>spare soap</li>
    <li>unopened shampoo</li>
    <li>backup razors</li>
    <li>replacement toothbrush heads</li>
    <li>unopened skincare</li>
    <li>guest toiletries</li>
    <li>extra cotton pads</li>
    <li>spare toilet paper</li>
    <li>travel toiletries</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Daily items should be easy to reach. Spare items can usually sit lower, further back, in
    labelled containers or outside the bathroom if space is limited.
  </p>
  <p>
    Do not give spare products the easiest positions unless they are used often.
  </p>

  <h2>Remove expired, empty and unused products</h2>
  <p>
    Many vanity problems come from products that should no longer be there.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying any organiser, check for:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>empty bottles</li>
    <li>expired products</li>
    <li>old makeup</li>
    <li>products that smell unusual</li>
    <li>products that have changed texture</li>
    <li>duplicate items</li>
    <li>travel products that are no longer needed</li>
    <li>almost-empty bottles kept for too long</li>
    <li>products that caused irritation</li>
    <li>samples that were never used</li>
    <li>broken packaging</li>
    <li>items that belong in another room</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Removing unused items may solve more than buying new containers.
  </p>
  <p>
    For medicines, skincare, cosmetics and first-aid items, follow product labels and
    appropriate disposal guidance. Do not keep questionable items simply because there is room
    in a drawer.
  </p>

  <h2>Sort by routine</h2>
  <p>
    A vanity organiser works well when it matches the way the household gets ready.
  </p>
  <p>Sort items into routine groups.</p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Routine group</th>
        <th>Examples</th>
        <th>Storage approach</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Morning routine</td>
        <td>toothbrush, cleanser, deodorant, sunscreen</td>
        <td>easy-reach tray, drawer or small basket</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Shower-adjacent routine</td>
        <td>razor, hair product, body lotion</td>
        <td>near bathroom use, but not crowded in wet zones</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Makeup routine</td>
        <td>daily makeup, brushes, remover</td>
        <td>drawer tray, upright holder or grouped container</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Hair routine</td>
        <td>brush, ties, clips, styling products</td>
        <td>drawer, cup, basket or heat-aware storage</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Shaving routine</td>
        <td>razor, blades, shaving cream</td>
        <td>controlled access and dry storage</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Backup supplies</td>
        <td>spare toothpaste, soap, blades</td>
        <td>labelled container or lower shelf</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Occasional products</td>
        <td>masks, treatments, travel items</td>
        <td>separate from daily-use space</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    This stops unrelated items from competing for the same small drawer or shelf.
  </p>

  <h2>Measure drawers before buying dividers</h2>
  <p>
    Bathroom vanity drawers vary widely.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying drawer organisers, measure:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>internal drawer width</li>
    <li>internal drawer depth</li>
    <li>internal drawer height</li>
    <li>usable height below the drawer frame</li>
    <li>whether plumbing reduces drawer depth</li>
    <li>whether the drawer has curved or cut-out sections</li>
    <li>whether organisers will stop the drawer closing</li>
    <li>whether handles or lids add height</li>
    <li>whether the drawer can open fully in the room</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Many vanity drawers are shallow. Some have cut-outs around pipes. Others are deep but
    narrow. A drawer organiser that works in a kitchen may not suit a bathroom vanity.
  </p>
  <p>
    Measure the actual internal drawer, not the outside of the vanity.
  </p>

  <h2>Check item height before choosing trays</h2>
  <p>
    Bathroom products are often taller than expected.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying trays or dividers, check whether items need to lie flat or stand upright.
  </p>
  <p>Items to measure include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>deodorant</li>
    <li>toothpaste</li>
    <li>moisturiser</li>
    <li>sunscreen</li>
    <li>cleanser bottles</li>
    <li>foundation bottles</li>
    <li>makeup brushes</li>
    <li>hair brushes</li>
    <li>razors</li>
    <li>electric toothbrush heads</li>
    <li>contact lens solution</li>
    <li>shaving cream</li>
    <li>skincare tubes</li>
    <li>cotton bud containers</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A tray may fit the drawer but not the products. If bottles need to lie down, check
    whether leaks are possible. If they need to stand upright, check whether the drawer or
    shelf height allows it.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep the benchtop limited</h2>
  <p>
    The vanity benchtop is often prime bathroom space. It should not become the default place
    for everything.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying benchtop organisers, decide what genuinely needs to stay out.</p>
  <p>Good candidates may include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>toothbrushes</li>
    <li>hand soap</li>
    <li>one or two daily-use products</li>
    <li>a small tray for morning routine items</li>
    <li>a cup or holder where suitable</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Poor candidates may include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>every skincare product</li>
    <li>spare toothpaste</li>
    <li>old makeup</li>
    <li>cleaning products</li>
    <li>medicines</li>
    <li>razors within child reach</li>
    <li>bulky baskets</li>
    <li>products that collect water and residue</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Benchtop organisers can make clutter look deliberate, but they can also make the vanity
    harder to wipe down. In a bathroom, cleaning access matters.
  </p>
  <p>
    If the bench still looks crowded after adding an organiser, the problem is probably too
    many items, not too little storage.
  </p>

  <h2>Check under-sink space carefully</h2>
  <p>
    Under-sink vanity storage is useful, but it is often awkward.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying under-sink organisers, measure and check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>pipe position</li>
    <li>trap position</li>
    <li>shelf height</li>
    <li>cabinet width</li>
    <li>cabinet depth</li>
    <li>door hinge clearance</li>
    <li>whether baskets can slide out</li>
    <li>whether the organiser blocks plumbing access</li>
    <li>whether products can stand upright</li>
    <li>whether leaks or spills would be visible</li>
    <li>whether cleaning access remains possible</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Do not force organisers around pipes. An under-sink organiser should fit the space
    without blocking access to plumbing or making leaks harder to notice.
  </p>
  <p>
    If the area is damp or has signs of water damage, do not treat storage as the fix. Seek
    appropriate advice for the underlying issue.
  </p>

  <h2>Be careful with medicines and first-aid items</h2>
  <p>
    Vanities often become the default place for medicines and first aid, but bathrooms can be
    humid and warm.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before storing medicines in a vanity, check product labels or pharmacist guidance. Some
    items may need to be stored away from moisture, heat or children.
  </p>
  <p>Be cautious with:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>prescription medicines</li>
    <li>children's medicines</li>
    <li>tablets and capsules</li>
    <li>creams and ointments</li>
    <li>thermometers</li>
    <li>bandages</li>
    <li>antiseptics</li>
    <li>first-aid tools</li>
    <li>expired medicines</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If medicines remain in the bathroom, they should be clearly separated and controlled, not
    mixed into general vanity clutter.
  </p>
  <p>
    Do not use ordinary open baskets for medicines where children or pets can access them.
  </p>

  <h2>Control razors, blades and sharp items</h2>
  <p>
    Razors and blades need deliberate storage.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying drawer trays or open organisers, decide how sharp items will be controlled.
  </p>
  <p>Items needing caution include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>razors</li>
    <li>spare blades</li>
    <li>scissors</li>
    <li>tweezers</li>
    <li>nail tools</li>
    <li>hair-cutting tools</li>
    <li>eyebrow tools</li>
    <li>small grooming blades</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Avoid storing loose blades in general drawers. Avoid placing razors where children can
    reach them easily. Also avoid leaving razors in damp areas where they sit in water.
  </p>
  <p>
    A vanity organiser should make sharp items easier to manage, not easier to grab
    accidentally.
  </p>

  <h2>Sort makeup and skincare by what is actually used</h2>
  <p>
    Makeup and skincare can fill a vanity quickly.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying cosmetic organisers, sort products into:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>daily use</li>
    <li>occasional use</li>
    <li>unopened backups</li>
    <li>expired or questionable</li>
    <li>wrong colour or unsuitable</li>
    <li>travel-size items</li>
    <li>samples</li>
    <li>brushes and tools</li>
    <li>products that should be stored away from heat or moisture</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Cosmetic organisers can make products look neat, but they do not solve overbuying or
    expired items.
  </p>
  <p>
    Keep daily products easy to reach. Store occasional items separately. Remove products that
    are no longer used or should not be kept.
  </p>

  <h2>Plan hair tool storage carefully</h2>
  <p>
    Hair tools can be awkward because they may involve heat, cords and electrical use.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying storage for hair tools, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>tool size</li>
    <li>cord length</li>
    <li>whether the tool needs to cool before storage</li>
    <li>where power points are located</li>
    <li>whether cords will cross wet areas</li>
    <li>whether the storage keeps the tool away from water</li>
    <li>whether children or pets can access it</li>
    <li>whether the organiser suits the tool shape</li>
    <li>whether the product instructions give storage guidance</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Do not create makeshift electrical setups or store hot tools in unsuitable containers.
    Follow manufacturer guidance for use and storage.
  </p>
  <p>
    If a hair tool is rarely used, it may not need prime vanity space.
  </p>

  <h2>Separate cleaning products from grooming products</h2>
  <p>
    Cleaning products do not belong mixed in with toothbrushes, skincare or cosmetics.
  </p>
  <p>
    If cleaning products are stored in the vanity, keep them clearly separated and controlled.
  </p>
  <p>Check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>product label storage instructions</li>
    <li>child and pet access</li>
    <li>whether products could leak</li>
    <li>whether bottles stand upright</li>
    <li>whether cloths or brushes need to dry</li>
    <li>whether the products should be stored elsewhere</li>
    <li>whether incompatible products need separation</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Do not store cleaning products above face-level daily items where leaks could drip onto
    them. Do not put hazardous products in unlabelled baskets.
  </p>
  <p>
    For cleaning products, follow product labels and seek appropriate advice where needed.
  </p>

  <h2>Think about shared bathrooms</h2>
  <p>
    Shared bathrooms need more deliberate vanity storage.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying organisers, check whether each person needs:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>a drawer zone</li>
    <li>a labelled basket</li>
    <li>a shared daily tray</li>
    <li>separate skincare or shaving areas</li>
    <li>a place for hair accessories</li>
    <li>a place for children's items</li>
    <li>a guest item zone</li>
    <li>backup supplies stored separately</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Shared vanities often become messy because one person's daily items become another
    person's clutter.
  </p>
  <p>
    A simple zone for each person can work better than one large mixed organiser.
  </p>

  <h2>Consider children and pets</h2>
  <p>
    Bathroom vanities often contain items that should not be accessible to children or pets.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying open storage, check whether it would expose:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>medicines</li>
    <li>razors</li>
    <li>blades</li>
    <li>cleaning products</li>
    <li>cosmetics</li>
    <li>fragrances</li>
    <li>small items that could be swallowed</li>
    <li>hot hair tools</li>
    <li>glass containers</li>
    <li>sharp grooming tools</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Low drawers and open baskets may be convenient, but they may not suit all households.
  </p>
  <p>
    Controlled storage matters more than a neat appearance.
  </p>

  <h2>Check moisture and cleaning access</h2>
  <p>
    Vanity storage should not create damp, hidden or hard-to-clean areas.
  </p>
  <p>Before buying containers, check whether they will:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>trap water</li>
    <li>hide spills</li>
    <li>block airflow</li>
    <li>make drawers harder to clean</li>
    <li>collect toothpaste residue</li>
    <li>sit under possible leaks</li>
    <li>hold damp cloths</li>
    <li>make bottles harder to wipe</li>
    <li>crowd the bench</li>
    <li>create mould-prone corners</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Choose organisers that can be removed and cleaned. Avoid storing damp items in closed
    containers.
  </p>
  <p>
    If vanity cabinets smell damp or show signs of mould or water damage, deal with the
    underlying issue rather than simply adding organisers.
  </p>

  <h2>Decide between trays, baskets, dividers and containers</h2>
  <p>
    Different vanity organisers solve different problems.
  </p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Organiser type</th>
        <th>Works well for</th>
        <th>Check before buying</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Drawer dividers</td>
        <td>makeup, grooming tools, toothbrush heads</td>
        <td>drawer height, layout, cleanability</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Small trays</td>
        <td>daily-use items, grouped products</td>
        <td>water collection, bench space</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Baskets</td>
        <td>spare supplies, grouped items</td>
        <td>moisture, label visibility, cleaning</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Clear containers</td>
        <td>visible categories, backup products</td>
        <td>size, lid fit, visual clutter</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Pull-out organisers</td>
        <td>under-sink access</td>
        <td>pipe clearance, cabinet depth</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Upright holders</td>
        <td>brushes, combs, selected tools</td>
        <td>height, stability, cleaning</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Lidded containers</td>
        <td>occasional items, backup supplies</td>
        <td>moisture risk, labels, access</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    A useful vanity setup usually uses a few simple organisers rather than a container for
    every product.
  </p>

  <h2>Common bathroom vanity storage mistakes</h2>
  <p>Before buying, avoid these mistakes:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>buying organisers before removing expired products</li>
    <li>measuring the outside of the vanity instead of the inside</li>
    <li>choosing drawer trays that are too tall</li>
    <li>buying under-sink organisers without checking pipes</li>
    <li>storing medicines in a humid area without checking guidance</li>
    <li>mixing cleaning products with grooming products</li>
    <li>leaving razors and blades loose in drawers</li>
    <li>using baskets that hide leaks or spills</li>
    <li>storing too many spare supplies in the vanity</li>
    <li>filling the benchtop with organisers</li>
    <li>choosing containers that make cleaning harder</li>
    <li>ignoring child and pet access</li>
    <li>buying cosmetic organisers for products that should be removed</li>
    <li>storing hot hair tools without checking manufacturer guidance</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A vanity organiser should make the bathroom easier to use and clean, not just make
    clutter look tidier.
  </p>

  <h2>A simple bathroom vanity checklist</h2>
  <p>Before buying vanity organisers, write down:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>what is used daily</li>
    <li>what is used weekly</li>
    <li>what is expired or unused</li>
    <li>what can be moved elsewhere</li>
    <li>drawer width, depth and height</li>
    <li>under-sink pipe position</li>
    <li>cabinet depth and shelf spacing</li>
    <li>whether products need to stand upright</li>
    <li>whether labels will be visible</li>
    <li>what needs controlled access</li>
    <li>medicines or first-aid items needing label or pharmacist guidance</li>
    <li>razors, blades and sharp tools</li>
    <li>makeup and skincare categories</li>
    <li>hair tool size and storage guidance</li>
    <li>cleaning products needing separation</li>
    <li>child and pet access risks</li>
    <li>moisture, dampness or leak concerns</li>
    <li>whether organisers can be removed and cleaned</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Take these notes before buying. Vanity storage usually fails when the products are not
    sorted first.
  </p>

  <h2>Our take</h2>
  <p>
    Bathroom vanity storage should start with sorting, not buying.
  </p>
  <p>
    Remove expired, empty and unused products first. Separate daily items from spare supplies.
    Measure drawers, shelves and under-sink spaces before buying trays, baskets or pull-out
    organisers. Be cautious with medicines, razors, cleaning products, hair tools, moisture
    and child access.
  </p>
  <p>
    For most households, a practical vanity setup is simple: daily items easy to reach, spare
    items grouped and labelled, sharp or hazardous items controlled, and organisers that can
    be cleaned easily.
  </p>
  <p>
    If an organiser hides expired products, blocks plumbing access, traps moisture or makes
    the benchtop harder to wipe, it is not solving the real problem.
  </p>

